You‚Äôre mixing two scopes:

- `round.set(roundIndex, i)` writes to the **Round** scope.
- `p.round.get(roundIndex)` reads from the **PlayerRound** scope.

Those are different. A value set on `round` is **not** visible on `p.round` unless you copy it there. That‚Äôs why `p.round.get(roundIndex)` was `undefined` earlier.

Also, small correction: Empirica has **many stages per round**, not many rounds per stage. A `stage` belongs to exactly one `round`. So it‚Äôs fine to use the current round‚Äôs index during `onStageStart`.

### Minimal, safe fix (no reliance on `{ round }` in stage callback)

1) Mirror the roundIndex into each player‚Äôs round **once per round**:

```js
Empirica.onRoundStart(({ game, round }) => {
  const idx = Number(round.get(roundIndex) ?? 0);
  for (const p of game.players) {
    p.round.set(roundIndex, idx); // <-- copy from Round -> PlayerRound
  }
});
```

2) Now your `onStageStart` can do exactly what you wanted:

```js
Empirica.onStageStart(({ stage }) => {
  const game = stage.currentGame;
  const attr = chatV2;

  for (const p of game.players) {
    const roundIndex = Number(p.round.get(roundIndex) ?? 0); // now defined üëç

    // image per player per round (but see note below about repeats)
    const imgs = sampleImages();        // returns 9 picks (3x3)
    const image = imgs[roundIndex % imgs.length];
    const avatarPath = toPublicPath(image);

    p.set(avatar, image);             // if you want avatar to change each round
    p.round.set(image, image);

    if (!Array.isArray(p.round.get(attr))) p.round.set(attr, []);

    // ... your kickoff message logic ...
  }
});
```

### Why this works
- You keep using `p.round.get(...)` in `onStageStart`, but now the value exists because you copied it from `round` in `onRoundStart`.

### One more gotcha (optional, but important)
Your `sampleImages()` returns **9** images each call (and it‚Äôs re-randomized every stage). If you have more than 9 rounds, `roundIndex % imgs.length` will start reusing images. If you truly want **no repeats within a player across all rounds**, give each player a prebuilt deck sized to your total round count (as in my previous message), or at least build it once per player in `onGameStart` and index into it with `roundIndex` instead of calling `sampleImages()` every stage.

If you‚Äôre fine with possible repeats after 9 rounds, your current modulo approach is OK.

That stack trace means you‚Äôre calling `.get(...)` on **something that‚Äôs undefined** inside your `onStageStart`. In your current flow, the usual culprit is **`p.round`** not being set yet for some player you‚Äôre looping over.

Two key points to fix this cleanly:

1) **Scope reality check:** a stage belongs to exactly one round (many stages per round, not many rounds per stage). So using the current round‚Äôs index during `stage.start` is valid.

2) **Player scope can be absent at stage start:** depending on timing, `game.players` can include folks who aren‚Äôt in this round/stage yet, so `p.round` can be `undefined`. Guard it‚Äîor iterate the players actually in this round/stage.

---

## Minimal, robust patch

Mirror the round index once per round, and be defensive in `stage.start`:

```js
// 1) Mirror the roundIndex into each player's round once per round
Empirica.onRoundStart(({ game, round }) => {
  const idx = Number(round.get(roundIndex) ?? 0);
  for (const p of game.players) {
    if (p.round) p.round.set(roundIndex, idx);   // <-- guard: p.round may not exist yet
  }
});

// 2) Use safe player list + guards in stage.start
Empirica.onStageStart(({ stage }) => {
  const game  = stage.currentGame;
  const round = stage.currentRound;
  if (!game || !round) return;                      // hard guard

  // Prefer players actually in this round/stage if available
  const players =
    (typeof round.getPlayers === function && round.getPlayers()) ||
    (typeof stage.getPlayers === function && stage.getPlayers()) ||
    game.players;

  const attr = chatV2;

  for (const p of players) {
    if (!p || !p.round) continue;                   // <-- guard fixes reading 'get'

    // Prefer the mirrored value; fall back to Round scope if needed
    const roundIndex =
      Number(p.round.get(roundIndex)) ??
      Number(round.get(roundIndex)) ??
      0;

    // (A) ensure per-player decks exist once
    if (!p.get(greetings_order)) p.set(greetings_order, shuffled(greetings));
    if (!p.get(image_deck)) {
      // build a per-player deck; or use your sampleImages() if you‚Äôre OK with repeats after 9
      const universe = allImages();                  // returns 147 names (man/woman/neutral)
      p.set(image_deck, shuffled(universe));
    }

    // (B) select this round‚Äôs items (no repeats within player if deck large enough)
    const deck = p.get(image_deck);
    const img  = deck[roundIndex % deck.length];    // safe index, even if deck shorter than rounds
    p.round.set(image, img);

    // Optional: stable avatar for this player
    if (!p.get(avatar_url)) p.set(avatar_url, toPublicPath(deck[0]));
    const avatarPath = p.get(avatar_url);

    // (C) ensure chat vector exists
    if (!Array.isArray(p.round.get(attr))) p.round.set(attr, []);

    // (D) kickoff message, one per player per round
    const msgs = p.round.get(attr) || [];
    const already = msgs.some(m => m && m.tag === kickoff && m.for === p.id);

    const order = p.get(greetings_order) || greetings;
    const text  = order[roundIndex % order.length] || Hi!;

    if (!already) {
      p.round.append(attr, {
        text,
        sender: { id: p.id, name: Other Player, avatar: avatarPath },
        createdAt: Date.now(),
        tag: kickoff,
        for: p.id,
      });
    }
  }
});
```

### Why your error happened
- You were doing `p.round.get(...)` when `p.round` didn‚Äôt exist yet for some `p`. That yields `TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'get')`.

### If you‚Äôd rather not mirror `roundIndex`
You can read from the Round scope directly and avoid the PlayerRound copy:

```js
const roundIndex = Number(round.get(roundIndex) ?? 0);
```

‚Ä¶but still **keep the `if (!p || !p.round) continue;` guard** to prevent the same error.

### Bonus: if you truly want ‚Äúplayers in this stage‚Äù
If your Empirica version exposes these helpers, use them:

```js
const players = round.getPlayers?.() || stage.getPlayers?.() || game.players;
```

That keeps you from touching players who aren‚Äôt actually in the current stage yet, which also avoids `p.round` being undefined.

Short answer: **use `stage.currentRound`, not `stage.round`.**  
In Empirica, a stage belongs to exactly one round (many stages per round, not many rounds per stage). On server callbacks, `stage` typically exposes a reference to that round as `stage.currentRound`. `stage.round` is usually **undefined**.

Here‚Äôs the safe pattern:

```js
Empirica.onStageStart(({ stage }) => {
